            BEAD
        #tabs-3.content
          %br
          %p
            Use the question, Can Every Good Boy Do Fine At Chess?, and the word, BEAD, to create and play the twelve major triad chords on a piano.
          %p
            A major triad is a group of three particular notes in a major scale. These three notes are the tonic or first note of the major scale,
            the third note of the major scale, and the fifth note of the major scale.
          %p
            The tonic of the major scale becomes the root of the major chord.
            The third note becomes the major third of the chord relative. The fifth note becomes the major fifth of the chord. 
          %p
            There are twelve major triads. On a piano keyboard, the root note is a white key for seven of the major triads and a black key for the other five major triads.
        #tabs-4.content
          %br
          %p
            To create a major triad chord, select the first letter of three consecutive words in The Question, then use The Word to put the sharps in the right places.
          %p
            If the root note of the chord is a letter in the word, BEAD, add a sharp to the note in the middle, the third.
          %p
            If the root note is B, add a sharp to the last note, the fifth, too.
        #tabs-5.content
          %br
          %p
            Can Every Good Boy Do Fine At Chess?
          %p
            C major triad: The three consecutive words are Can Every Good => C E G. Since C is not in the word BEAD, there are no sharps.
          %p
            A major triad: The three consecutive words are At Chess?/Can Every => A C E. Since A is in the word BEAD, add a sharp to C => A C# E.
          %p
            The rest are...
          %table
            %tr
              %td
                B
              %td
                \=> Boy Do Fine
              %td
                \=> B D F => add sharps
              %td
                \=> B D# F# 
            %tr
              %td
                D
              %td
                \=> Do Fine At
              %td
                \=> D F A => add sharp
              %td
                \=> D F# A
            %tr
              %td
                E
              %td
                \=> Every Good Boy
              %td
                \=> E G B => add sharp
              %td
                \=> E G# B
            %tr
              %td
                F
              %td
                \=> Fine At Chess
              %td
                \=> F A C
            %tr
              %td
                G
              %td
                \=> Good Boy Do
              %td
                \=> G B D
          %p
            You now know how to create every major triad chord with the root note on a white key.
        #tabs-6.content
          %br
          %p
            The black keys are Bb, Eb, Ab, Db, and Gb, also known as, A#, D#, G#, C#, and F#.
          %p
            The same three notes in a major triad starting on a white key are in the major chord triad start on a black key, but they are shifted down a half step from the positions for the white keys. To move down a half step on a piano, move one key to the left.
          %p
            For these major chords, the natural notes become flat notes, and the sharp notes become natural notes.
          %table
            %tr
              %td
                Bb
              %td
                \=> Boy Do Fine
              %td
                \=> Bb D F
            %tr
              %td
                Eb
              %td
                \=> Every Good Boy
              %td
                \=> Eb G Bb
            %tr
              %td
                Ab
              %td
                \=> At Chess?/Can Every
              %td
                \=> Ab C Eb
            %tr
              %td
                Db
              %td
                \=> Do Fine At
              %td
                \=> Db F Ab
            %tr
              %td
                Gb
              %td
                \=> Good Boy Do
              %td
                \=> Gb Bb Db
