        #major_scale
          %br
          %p
            A major scale has eight notes, but two notes are the same, the root (first note) and the octave (eighth note).
          %p
            Now that you have mastered major triads, you know three of these notes.
            You will now learn the other four notes.
          %p
            A half-step or a whole step up or down from a note in the major triad will land on another note in the major scale.
          %table
            %tr
              %td
                Second or Ninth Note (2 + 7 = 9)
              %td
                \=> a whole step up from the root or a whole step down from the third note
            %tr
              %td
                Fourth or Eleventh Note (4 + 7 = 11)
              %td
                \=> a half step up from the third note or a whole step down from the fifth note
            %tr
              %td
                Sixth or Thirteenth Note (6 + 7 = 13)
              %td
                \=> a whole step up from the fifth note
            %tr
              %td
                Seventh note
              %td
                \=> a half step down from the root (octave)
                
          %h3
            Activity

          %p
            Play the root on the keyboard to pick the key of the major scale. A scale degree (2nd, 3rd,..., 13th) is displayed above the keyboard.
            Play that note on the keyboard.
          %p
            For example, if you press C as the root, and 5th appears as the scale degree, then you should press G.
          %p
            If you are right, you will be serenaded with a quick rendition of the scale, then the next degree appears.
          %p
            To change the root, move the mouse off and back onto the keyboard picture, then play the new root.
            
